03923nam a22005415i 9781478023531DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20222022ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780235317 a10.1515/97814780235312doi  a(DE-B1597)642215  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aLB1072b.S685 2022 7aEDU0570002bisacsh04a370.15/34223/eng/202204211 aSpringgay, Stephanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFeltness :bResearch-Creation, Socially Engaged Art, and Affective Pedagogies /cStephanie Springgay. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Feltness: On How to Practice Intimacy -- tChapter One. Bitter Chocolate Is for Adults! Matters of Taste in Elementary Students’ Socially Engaged Art -- tChapter Two. Imponderable Curricula: Living the Future Now -- tChapter Three. Fluxus and the Event Score: The Ordinary Potential of Radical Pedagogy as Art -- tChapter Four. Anarchiving as Research-Creation: Instant Class Kit -- tChapter Five. Conditions of Feltness -- tChapter Six. Make a Public -- tChapter Seven. Pedagogical Impulses -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStephanie Springgay’s concept of feltness—which emerges from affect theory, queer and feminist theory, and feminist conceptions of more-than-human entanglements—is a set of intimate practices of creating art based on touch, affect, relationality, love, and responsibility. In this book, she explores how feltness is a radical pedagogy that can be practiced with diverse publics, including children, who are often left out of conversations about who can learn in radical ways. Springgay examines the results of a decade-long project in which researchers, artists, students, and teachers participated in events in North American elementary, secondary, and postsecondary institutions. In projects that ranged from children learning to be critics and artists to university students experimenting with building “a public” through art, participants blended participatory art creation with academic research to address social justice issues. Springgay shows how feltness can redefine who is imagined to be capable of complex feeling, experiential learning, embodied practice, social engagement, and intimate care. In this way, feltness fosters learning that disrupts and defamiliarizes schools and institutions, knowledge systems, values, and the legibility of art and research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aAffect (Psychology) in art. 0aAffective educationxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aAffective educationzUnited States. 0aArts in educationzUnited States. 0aFeminist theory. 7aEDUCATION / Arts in Education.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478023531?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478023531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478023531/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles